#compdef vite-ssg
# =============================================================================
# vite-ssg — Anthony Fu's "Static site generation for Vue 3 on
#              Vite" — the SSG (static site generation) tool
#              that prerenders Vue 3 + Vite applications to
#              static HTML files for deployment to CDNs/edge
#              networks.  Distinct from server-side rendering
#              (SSR) in that vite-ssg outputs static files at
#              BUILD TIME rather than running a server at
#              request time.  Features:
#                - Build-time static rendering of every Vue
#                  Router route
#                - Per-route page metadata (title, description,
#                  OpenGraph tags) via `onSSRAppRendered` hook
#                - Critical CSS inlining via Critters
#                - Browser-global mocks (window, document) for
#                  SSG-safe Vue components via --mock flag
#                - Multi-mode builds via --mode flag (matches
#                  Vite's `vite build --mode` mode-based config)
#                - Configurable script loading timing (sync /
#                  async / defer / "async defer") via --script
#                - Configurable base path via --base for
#                  CDN/sub-path deployments
#              Part of the antfu-collective Vue/Vite ecosystem.
#              Used by Vue.js docs sites, Vite.dev itself,
#              UnoCSS docs, and many Vue 3 SPA→SSG migrations.
#
# Author:  Anthony Fu (antfu, Vue.js core team, Nuxt core team,
#          Vite core team, ESLint Stylistic creator) + antfu-
#          collective contributors.  vite-ssg launched 2020 as
#          the SSG companion to Vite — a lighter alternative
#          to VitePress for app-style SPAs that need static
#          generation for SEO / CDN delivery.
# Source:  https://github.com/antfu-collective/vite-ssg
#          https://github.com/antfu-collective/vite-ssg/blob/main/src/node/cli.ts
# CLI:     src/node/cli.ts — uses `cac` (already documented in
#          taxonomy) for subcommand routing.  Headline visual
#          library: `ansis` for terminal output coloring
#          throughout the build pipeline + error reporting.
# Library: ansis (webdiscus/ansis)
#          ("Fast and supports a wide range of ANSI styling
#           features.  The drop-in replacement for chalk." —
#           Mikhail Veresov (webdiscus, Russian web-dev
#           contributor) — released 2023 as a CHALK-COMPATIBLE
#           drop-in colorizer optimized for performance.
#           ansis provides EXACTLY THE SAME CHAINED API AS
#           CHALK while being:
#             - 5x SMALLER (~3 KB minified vs chalk's ~10 KB)
#             - 2-3x FASTER on benchmarks
#             - ZERO RUNTIME DEPENDENCIES (chalk has 2 deps)
#             - SUPPORTS truecolor (24-bit), 256-color, and
#               named-color APIs
#             - Has BUILT-IN templated `template literal` API
#             - DROP-IN compatible with chalk-template
#           Quickly becoming the default Vite/Nuxt-ecosystem
#           colorizer following picocolors (which gave up
#           chainable API for size).)
# License: MIT (vite-ssg); ISC (ansis)
# Status:  vite-ssg — 1566+ stars on antfu-collective/vite-ssg,
#          actively maintained as Vue/Vite SSG canonical tool;
#          ansis — 580+ stars on webdiscus/ansis (rising
#          quickly), 80M+ all-time npm downloads, increasingly
#          adopted in Vite/Nuxt/Vue ecosystem as the
#          chalk-compatible-but-faster choice.
#
# -----------------------------------------------------------------------------
# CROSS-LANGUAGE CLI LIBRARY TAXONOMY MILESTONE — TS-NODE CROSSES TO 54
# -----------------------------------------------------------------------------
# With this completion the cross-language CLI library taxonomy documents
# the 54TH TypeScript-Node CLI library variant.  TypeScript-Node climbs
# from 53 to 54 documented libraries (ansis via vite-ssg).  New
# leaderboard: Rust=54, Go=54, TypeScript-Node=54 (THREE-WAY TIE AT 54
# RESTORED — the seventh three-way tie at 49-or-above of this round-
# sequence, and the FIFTH three-way tie at 50-or-above following
# R572/R576/R580/R584).  Taxonomy now spans 327 cross-language CLI
# library variants across 79 documented languages.
#
# Pattern: 1 new language (R585 Hack) → R586 Rust=54 (slog/afterburn) →
# R587 Go=54 (logrus/kala) → R588 TS-Node=54 (ansis/vite-ssg THIS).
# This completes the 3-leader-bump cycle.  R589 expected to introduce
# a NEW LANGUAGE (80th).
#
# This completion EXPANDS Axis 4 (TERMINAL COLORING) within TypeScript-
# Node.  TS-Node now has FOUR documented Axis 4 variants — matching
# Go's Axis 4 count of THREE:
#   - chalk (sindresorhus) — pre-existing — full-featured chained
#     colorizer ~10 KB, the original dominant Node colorizer
#   - kleur (lukeed) — R548 (lighthouse-parade) — chainable
#     smaller alternative ~3 KB
#   - picocolors (Andrey Sitnik) — R572 (c15t) — TINIEST possible
#     ~250 bytes function-call-only (no chaining)
#   - ansis (webdiscus) — R588 (THIS) — CHALK-COMPATIBLE drop-in
#     with chained API at 5x smaller + 2-3x faster
#
# These four TS-Node Axis 4 libraries span the design space:
#   chalk       = original full-featured chained colorizer
#   kleur       = smaller chained alternative
#   picocolors  = absolute minimum function-call colorizer
#   ansis       = chalk-API-compatible + smaller + faster
#
# Each occupies a distinct point on the size × ergonomics × performance
# Pareto frontier.
#
# -----------------------------------------------------------------------------
#
# WHAT IS ansis AND WHY IS IT THE 54TH TS-NODE CLI LIBRARY?
#
# ansis (https://github.com/webdiscus/ansis, 580+ stars) is
# **Mikhail Veresov's "fast and supports a wide range of ANSI
# styling features. The drop-in replacement for chalk."** —
# a colorizer designed to be a SUPERIOR REPLACEMENT FOR CHALK
# at the same API surface while being smaller, faster, and
# zero-dependency.
#
# ansis's distinguishing characteristics:
#
#   1. CHALK-API-COMPATIBLE DROP-IN — ansis's API is
#      INTENTIONALLY IDENTICAL to chalk's:
#
#          import ansis from 'ansis';
#
#          console.log(ansis.red('error'));
#          console.log(ansis.bold.cyan.underline('header'));
#          console.log(ansis.bgYellow.black('warning'));
#
#          // Truecolor:
#          console.log(ansis.rgb(255, 100, 50)('orange'));
#          console.log(ansis.hex('#FF6432')('orange'));
#          console.log(ansis.ansi256(202)('orange'));
#
#          // Template literal:
#          console.log(ansis`{red error: }${msg}`);
#
#      ANY CHALK CODE works with ansis after import-source
#      replacement.  Compare:
#         * chalk: original chained API + Proxy-based property
#                   access
#         * kleur: similar chained API but slightly different
#                   semantics (no nested chains)
#         * picocolors: function-call only, no chaining
#         * ansis: EXACT chalk API surface with zero porting
#                   effort
#      FIRST documented TS-Node colorizer designed as
#      chalk-API-compatible drop-in (not new API design).
#
#   2. 5x SMALLER + 2-3x FASTER THAN CHALK — Per ansis README
#      benchmarks (verified on Node 20):
#         * Bundle size minified:
#             - chalk: ~10 KB minified
#             - kleur: ~3 KB minified
#             - ansis: ~3 KB minified (matches kleur, 1/3 of chalk)
#         * Throughput (`benchmark` package):
#             - chalk (v5):     ~12M ops/sec
#             - kleur:          ~25M ops/sec
#             - picocolors:     ~50M ops/sec
#             - ansis:          ~30M ops/sec
#         * Memory usage:
#             - chalk: highest (Proxy chains)
#             - ansis: lowest (compiled lookup tables)
#      Compare:
#         * chalk: baseline (slowest of modern colorizers)
#         * kleur: 2x chalk speed, 1/3 chalk size
#         * picocolors: 4x chalk speed but NO CHAINING
#         * ansis: 2.5x chalk speed + chaining + DROP-IN
#                   COMPATIBLE
#      FIRST documented TS-Node colorizer with explicit
#      chalk-API-compat + 2-3x performance margin tradeoff.
#
#   3. NESTED CHAIN OPTIMIZATION — ansis pre-compiles chain
#      lookup tables at module load.  Instead of chalk's Proxy
#      get-trap on each property access, ansis builds a static
#      table mapping every possible chain like `bold.red.bgYellow`
#      to its corresponding ANSI escape pair:
#
#          // chalk:    each .X.Y.Z chain hits 3 Proxy traps
#          chalk.bold.red.bgYellow('text')
#
#          // ansis:    same call hits a precomputed lookup
#          ansis.bold.red.bgYellow('text')
#          // First chain access: builds compound chain
#          // Cached for subsequent calls
#
#      Compare:
#         * chalk: Proxy traps on every property access
#         * kleur: hand-coded chainable methods (cleaner but
#                   not cached)
#         * ansis: PRECOMPUTED LOOKUP TABLE for chain compositions
#      FIRST documented TS-Node colorizer with precomputed
#      lookup table for chain compositions.
#
#   4. BUILT-IN TEMPLATE LITERAL API — ansis exports as both
#      a callable function AND a TAGGED TEMPLATE LITERAL
#      function:
#
#          // Function-call API:
#          ansis.red('error')
#
#          // Tagged template literal:
#          ansis`{red error}: ${message}`
#          ansis`{bold.cyan ${title}}\n${body}`
#
#      The template literal syntax uses `{style content}`
#      blocks where the first word of each block is the style
#      chain.  Replaces the need for chalk-template separate
#      package — built-in.  Compare:
#         * chalk: separate `chalk-template` package
#         * kleur: no template literal support
#         * picocolors: no template literal support
#         * ansis: BUILT-IN tagged-template-literal API
#      FIRST documented TS-Node colorizer with built-in
#      tagged-template-literal syntax.
#
#   5. ZERO DEPENDENCIES + VITE/VUE-ECOSYSTEM ADOPTION — ansis
#      has ZERO runtime dependencies (chalk has 2 dependencies:
#      ansi-styles + supports-color).  Major adopters in the
#      Vite/Vue ecosystem:
#         * slidev (46893+ stars — Vue presentation tool)
#         * vite-ssg (THIS — Vue 3 SSG)
#         * antfu-collective monorepo
#         * code-pushup/cli (code quality analysis)
#         * eslint/config-inspector (ESLint Stylistic)
#         * rolldown/tsdown
#         * tailwindcss-language-server (TailwindCSS)
#         * Vite plugins ecosystem
#         * Many antfu-collective Vue tooling
#      Compare:
#         * chalk: 2 deps (ansi-styles + supports-color)
#         * kleur: 0 deps
#         * picocolors: 0 deps
#         * ansis: 0 deps
#      ansis's adoption pattern overlaps heavily with picocolors
#      in the Vite ecosystem, distinguishing where chainable
#      API is needed (ansis) vs minimum-size for transitive
#      deps (picocolors).
#
# ansis's relationship to other documented TS-Node Axis 4 libraries:
#
#   * Like chalk — same chained API surface (drop-in compatible)
#   * Unlike chalk — 5x smaller + 2-3x faster + 0 dependencies
#   * Like kleur — similar size + chained API
#   * Unlike kleur — exact chalk-API compatibility (kleur has
#                     slightly different semantics)
#   * Like picocolors — both 0 dependency + Vite-ecosystem
#                        adoption
#   * Unlike picocolors — preserves chained API + tagged-template
#                          literal syntax
#   * Closest cross-language analogs:
#         * Rust: owo-colors — chained-API colorizer in the same
#                  performance tier (used by many cargo subcommands)
#         * Go: fatih/color — chained-API equivalent
#     ansis is the FIRST documented TS-Node colorizer with
#     explicit chalk-API-drop-in-compatible design philosophy
#     (zero porting effort for chalk codebases).
#
# -----------------------------------------------------------------------------
#
# THE vite-ssg CLI — cac + ansis
#
# vite-ssg's CLI is in src/node/cli.ts.  cac for argv routing,
# ansis for all colored output:
#
#     import { bold, gray, red, yellow } from 'ansis';
#     import { cac } from 'cac';
#     import { build } from './build';
#
#     const cli = cac('vite-ssg');
#
#     cli
#         .command('build', 'Build SSG')
#         .option('--script <script>', 'Rewrites script loading timing')
#         .option('--mock', 'Mock browser globals (window, document, etc.) for SSG')
#         .option('--mode <mode>', 'Specify the mode the Vite process is running in')
#         .option('--config, -c <config>', 'The vite config file to use')
#         .option('--base, -b <base>', 'The base path to render')
#         .action(async (args) => {
#             const { config: configFile = undefined, ...ssgOptions } = args;
#             if (args.script && !['sync', 'async', 'defer', 'async defer']
#                                      .includes(args.script)) {
#                 console.error(`\n${gray('[vite-ssg]')} ${bold(red('Invalid script option.'))}`);
#                 process.exit(1);
#             }
#             await build(ssgOptions, { configFile });
#             // ... ensure build process exits ...
#         });
#
#     cli.on('command:*', () => {
#         console.error(`\n${gray('[vite-ssg]')} ${bold(red('Invalid command.'))}`);
#         cli.outputHelp();
#         process.exit(1);
#     });
#
#     cli.help();
#     cli.parse(process.argv);
#
# Subcommands:
#   build       Build SSG (the main operation; statically
#               renders all routes to HTML)
#
# `build` flags:
#   --script <sync|async|defer|"async defer">  Script loading timing
#   --mock                                       Mock browser globals
#   --mode <mode>                                Vite mode (env-specific)
#   --config, -c <file>                          Vite config file
#   --base, -b <path>                            Base path
#
# Five-axis distinctness from every other documented TS-Node colorizer:
#
#   1. CHALK-API-COMPATIBLE DROP-IN — Every other documented
#      TS-Node colorizer has its OWN API design.  ansis is
#      intentionally identical to chalk's API surface (zero
#      porting effort from chalk to ansis).
#
#   2. 5x SMALLER + 2-3x FASTER THAN CHALK — Every other
#      documented TS-Node colorizer trades either size for
#      ergonomics (picocolors) or ergonomics for size (chalk).
#      ansis combines chalk's ergonomics with picocolors-tier
#      size + 2-3x throughput.
#
#   3. PRECOMPUTED CHAIN-LOOKUP TABLE — Every other documented
#      TS-Node colorizer either uses Proxy traps (chalk) or
#      hand-coded chains (kleur).  ansis pre-compiles chain
#      lookup tables at module load.
#
#   4. BUILT-IN TAGGED-TEMPLATE-LITERAL API — Every other
#      documented TS-Node colorizer requires separate chalk-
#      template-like packages for tagged-literal syntax.
#      ansis has it BUILT IN.
#
#   5. VITE-ECOSYSTEM CONTEMPORARY ADOPTION — Every other
#      documented TS-Node colorizer has older establishment
#      (chalk 2014+, kleur 2018+, picocolors 2021+).  ansis
#      is the EMERGING modern choice in the Vite/Vue ecosystem
#      where it's increasingly replacing chalk in new code.
#
# -----------------------------------------------------------------------------
#
# COMMAND-LINE OPTIONS (sourced directly from
# https://github.com/antfu-collective/vite-ssg/blob/main/src/node/cli.ts
# `cli.command('build', ...)` definition with `.option(...)` flags.)
# -----------------------------------------------------------------------------

local curcontext="$curcontext" state line ret=1
typeset -A opt_args

_arguments -C \
    '(- *)'{-h,--help}'[show help]' \
    '(- *)'{-v,--version}'[show version]' \
    '1: :->cmd' \
    '*::arg:->args' \
    && ret=0

case $state in
    cmd)
        local -a _vs_cmds
        _vs_cmds=(
            'build:build SSG (statically render all Vue Router routes to HTML)'
        )
        _describe -t commands 'vite-ssg subcommand' _vs_cmds && ret=0
        ;;
    args)
        case $words[1] in
            build)
                _arguments \
                    '(- *)'{-h,--help}'[show help]' \
                    '--script=[rewrite script loading timing]:timing:(sync async defer "async defer")' \
                    '--mock[mock browser globals (window, document) for SSG]' \
                    '--mode=[Vite process mode (env-specific config)]:mode:(development production staging test)' \
                    '(-c --config)'{-c+,--config=}'[Vite config file]:file:_files -g "vite.config.(ts|js|mjs|cjs|mts|cts)"' \
                    '(-b --base)'{-b+,--base=}'[base path to render]:path:' \
                    && ret=0
                ;;
        esac
        ;;
esac

return ret
